}

{
  "description": "A dashboard-style chart focused on retail performance after expansion. Main visual: a multi-series line chart with months on the x-axis from Jan to Oct and indexed values on the y-axis from 60 to 140. Series 1: Same-store sales index rises from 100 in Jan to 112 in Jun, then falls to 95 by Oct. Series 2: New-store sales vs target index starts at 98 in Jul, drops to 88 in Aug, 81 in Sep, and 76 in Oct. Series 3: Inventory on hand index stays near 100 through Jun, then climbs to 108 in Jul, 118 in Aug, 127 in Sep, and 135 in Oct. Add a vertical marker at Jul labeled '18 new stores opened'. Include a smaller secondary bar chart beneath showing regional performance for the new stores in Oct with cities on the x-axis and percent of sales target on the y-axis: Phoenix 82%, Charlotte 79%, Nashville 77%, Denver 84%, Tampa 75%, Columbus 80%. The visual should make clear that performance was strong in the first half, then sales declined while inventory built up and new stores underperformed across multiple promising markets.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Diagrama de fluxo do processo de compra destacando os pontos de falha recorrentes. Mostrar caixas conectadas por setas, em português, nesta sequência: 'Cliente inicia compra' -> 'Carrinho' -> 'Login/Cadastro' -> 'Endereço de entrega' -> 'Cálculo de frete' -> 'Escolha de pagamento' -> 'Antifraude' -> 'Autorização do pagamento' -> 'Emissão do pedido' -> 'Confirmação ao cliente'. Destacar em vermelho três etapas problemáticas: 'Cálculo de frete', 'Antifraude' e 'Autorização do pagamento'. Incluir pequenos ícones de alerta nessas caixas e setas tracejadas vermelhas mostrando que falhas nessas etapas afetam etapas seguintes. Adicionar anotações curtas ao lado dos pontos críticos: em 'Cálculo de frete' escrever 'timeout intermitente'; em 'Antifraude' escrever 'resposta inconsistente'; em 'Autorização do pagamento' escrever 'erro em cascata'. Visual com aparência de arquitetura de sistema/fluxo operacional, fundo claro, caixas em cinza e pontos críticos em vermelho para enfatizar que correções isoladas quebram outras partes do fluxo.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Flow diagram of the national vaccine rollout system highlighting likely bottlenecks. Show a left-to-right process with labeled nodes: 'Global manufacturers', 'National procurement', 'Customs clearance', 'Central cold storage', 'Regional distribution hubs', 'Local clinics and hospitals', and 'Population receiving vaccines'. Add arrows between each stage to show dose movement. Include side inputs and constraints as smaller connected nodes: to 'National procurement' connect 'Limited contracts', 'Budget approval delays'; to 'Customs clearance' connect 'Import paperwork backlog'; to 'Central cold storage' connect 'Insufficient ultra-cold freezers'; to 'Regional distribution hubs' connect 'Truck shortages', 'Fuel shortages'; to 'Local clinics and hospitals' connect 'Staff shortages', 'Appointment scheduling problems', 'Rural access barriers'. Visually emphasize delays with red warning icons or bottleneck markers at customs clearance, central cold storage, and regional distribution. Include uneven output from regional hubs by branching to 4 example regions: 'North - 40% of requested doses delivered on time', 'South - 82%', 'East - 55%', 'West - 68%'. Overall style should be a clean policy briefing diagram with arrows, labeled bottlenecks, and clear causal relationships showing why some regions wait while others receive late shipments.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "A cutaway illustration of a century-old stone building viewed from the side, showing three to four stories and a visible foundation. Emphasize the physical condition of the structure: fresh diagonal cracks running from the corners of upper-floor window openings, several thinner vertical cracks extending through interior plaster on the top two floors, and slight separation along mortar joints in the stone exterior. The lower foundation on one side should appear subtly settled, with the ground beneath it slightly sunken compared with the opposite side, suggesting uneven settlement. Show intact neighboring stone buildings on both sides with no visible cracks for comparison. Include realistic material details: aged gray-brown stone blocks, weathered mortar, old timber floor beams inside, and lighter-colored fresh crack surfaces contrasting with older darker masonry. The scene should communicate that damage is concentrated in the inspected building’s upper floors while nearby similar buildings remain unaffected.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "A network path diagram comparing the normal route to the slow-region route. Show two side-by-side paths from 'Users in Region A' and 'Users in Slow Region' to 'Web App Servers'. For the normal route, use 5 hops: 'Local ISP Router' -> 'Regional Backbone' -> 'Internet Exchange' -> 'Cloud Edge' -> 'Web App Servers', with a total latency label of about 45 ms. For the slow-region route, use 8 hops: 'Local ISP Router' -> 'Regional ISP Core' -> 'Transit Provider 1' -> 'Another City Peering Point' -> 'Transit Provider 2' -> 'Cloud Edge' -> 'Load Balancer' -> 'Web App Servers', with total latency shown as variable across tests: 2.4 s, 5.8 s, and 3.1 s. Mark the extra hops in the slow-region route in a contrasting color, especially the 'Another City Peering Point' stop. Add a note beside the slow route saying 'Hop count remains constant across repeated tests' and another note saying 'Delay varies by several seconds despite identical path length'. Use arrows to indicate traffic flow toward the app and small latency annotations under each route summary rather than per-hop timing.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Código em estilo Python mostrando um pipeline de tratamento de dados financeiros com conversões inconsistentes entre colunas semelhantes. Exibir um único arquivo com seções comentadas. Primeira seção: leitura inicial de um CSV com colunas `renda_mensal`, `limite_credito`, `divida_total` e `score_externo`, onde exemplos de valores aparecem misturados como strings: `\"4500,00\"`, `\"\"`, `None`, `\"NaN\"`, `\"7.200,50\"`, `\"--\"`. Segunda seção: uma função `parse_valor_bruto()` aplicada apenas a algumas colunas, convertendo `\"\"` para `0.0`, `None` para `0.0`, removendo pontos de milhar e trocando vírgula por ponto. Mostrar linhas como `df[\"renda_mensal\"] = df[\"renda_mensal\"].apply(parse_valor_bruto)` e `df[\"limite_credito\"] = pd.to_numeric(df[\"limite_credito\"], errors=\"coerce\")`, destacando que colunas parecidas usam tratamentos diferentes. Terceira seção: impressão intermediária de `df.dtypes` mostrando `renda_mensal float64`, `limite_credito float64`, `divida_total object`, `score_externo object`. Quarta seção: amostra de 5 linhas em comentário ou saída de log embutida, com casos como: linha 101 `renda_mensal=0.0` embora a origem estivesse vazia; linha 102 `divida_total=\"\"` ainda visível; linha 103 `score_externo=\"NaN\"`; linha 104 `limite_credito=nan`; linha 105 `divida_total=\"1.250,00\"`. Quinta seção: etapa final de fechamento do relatório com `fillna(0)` e `astype(float)` aplicada em lote, gerando problemas tardios em colunas que permaneceram como texto. Incluir comentário de alerta no código: `# vazios viram 0 cedo em algumas colunas, mas em outras só no fechamento`. Destacar visualmente com comentários ou marcadores de erro as linhas onde o comportamento inconsistente acontece.",
  "kind": "code"
}

{
  "description": "Gráfico de barras agrupadas en español que compare la distribución de dos variantes del producto en corridas buenas versus la corrida problemática. Título: \"Distribución de variantes del producto en corridas del proceso\". Eje X: \"Tipo de corrida\" con dos categorías: \"Corridas buenas\" y \"Corrida problemática\". Eje Y: \"Porcentaje relativo de variantes (%)\" de 0 a 100. Dos series de barras: \"Variante A\" y \"Variante B\". Valores ilustrativos: para \"Corridas buenas\", Variante A = 88% y Variante B = 12%; para \"Corrida problemática\", Variante A = 57% y Variante B = 43%. Añadir una nota visual o subtítulo que diga: \"Dos posiciones parecidas en el compuesto de partida pueden generar variantes distintas; normalmente la mezcla menor se mantiene baja, pero en esta corrida la proporción quedó desbalanceada\". Usar colores contrastantes, por ejemplo azul para Variante A y naranja para Variante B, con leyenda visible.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Line chart showing monthly same-store sales index and new-store sales index from January to October to illustrate an early seasonal pull-forward and a later decline. X-axis: Month (Jan, Feb, Mar, Apr, May, Jun, Jul, Aug, Sep, Oct). Y-axis: Sales Index where 100 = typical monthly plan. Include three series: 1) 'Same-store sales' with values 96, 118, 128, 121, 112, 106, 101, 95, 88, 84; 2) 'New-store sales' with values not applicable before openings, then 102 in Jul, 98 in Aug, 89 in Sep, 83 in Oct; 3) 'Baseline seasonal pattern' as a dashed line with values 100, 102, 108, 110, 107, 103, 101, 100, 99, 98. Add a shaded band over Feb to Apr labeled 'Holiday timing shift: seasonal demand pulled forward' and a narrower shaded band over late May to mid-Jun labeled 'Temporary foot-traffic surge'. Add callout markers on three example cities with the largest temporary boosts: 'Phoenix +18% vs plan in Jun, still 103 in Jul, then 91 in Sep', 'Charlotte +16% in Jun, 101 in Jul, 90 in Sep', and 'Nashville +14% in Jun, 104 in Jul, 92 in Sep'. The visual should emphasize that sales were boosted earlier than normal, some strong-boost cities remained relatively solid into midsummer, and the broader decline became clear later in late summer and early fall.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Diagrama de fluxo do processamento de pedidos destacando inconsistência temporária de status entre sistemas. Mostrar 5 blocos principais, da esquerda para a direita: 'Checkout', 'Serviço de Pedidos', 'Fila de Eventos', 'Serviço de Pagamento' e 'Banco de Leitura / Painéis e Consultas'. Do bloco 'Serviço de Pedidos' sair uma seta sólida para 'Banco principal' com rótulo 'grava status imediatamente'. Do mesmo bloco sair outra seta para 'Fila de Eventos', e da fila uma seta para 'Banco de Leitura / Painéis e Consultas' com rótulo 'atualização assíncrona, atraso de 2 a 5 min'. Acima do diagrama, incluir um exemplo de pedido problemático 'Pedido #48127': no 'Serviço de Pedidos' e 'Banco principal' o status aparece como 'concluído' às 14:03, enquanto no 'Banco de Leitura / Painéis e Consultas' aparece como 'pendente' até 14:06, quando então muda para 'concluído'. Destacar essa janela com uma faixa amarela escrita 'inconsistência temporária entre telas e consultas'. Abaixo, incluir um segundo exemplo 'Pedido #48135 com erro': todos os blocos mostram 'pendente' desde 14:03 até 14:10, com uma anotação verde 'estado consistente mesmo com falha'. Usar cores diferentes para status: verde para 'concluído', laranja para 'pendente'. O foco visual deve ser a diferença entre atualização imediata no sistema principal e atualização atrasada nas consultas, contrastada com casos em que o status permanece igual em todos os pontos.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "A flow diagram of the vaccine and supply request process with several offices in sequence and a few bypass paths. Show nodes as labeled boxes connected by arrows from left to right. Main path: 'Regional Clinic Request' -> 'District Health Office' -> 'Provincial Review' -> 'National Disease Taskforce' -> 'Procurement Unit' -> 'Factory / Central Warehouse' -> 'Shipment to Region'. Add a parallel path for laboratory materials: 'Sample Transfer' -> 'District Lab Office' -> 'Provincial Lab Review' -> 'National Reference Lab' -> 'Factory / Test Supply Unit'. Include a paperwork lane beneath the main flow: 'Reporting Form Submitted' -> 'Verification Desk' -> 'Approval Archive' -> 'Release Authorization'. Use thin gray arrows for standard movement and place small delay labels above several arrows such as '1-2 days', '2 days', '1 day', '3 days' to emphasize multi-office routing. Highlight two exceptions in red or orange: one shortcut arrow directly from 'National Disease Taskforce' to 'Factory / Central Warehouse' labeled 'Urgent message answered same day', and another shortcut from 'Procurement Unit' to 'Shipment to Region' labeled 'Materials sent before full reporting trail complete'. Add a note icon near the paperwork lane saying 'Documentation often completed after dispatch in some cases'. The visual should make clear that most requests pass through many administrative offices, while urgent cases sometimes bypass steps and move faster.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Grouped bar chart comparing average monthly sales index for new stores in two city groups from launch through month 5. X-axis: months since launch labeled Month 0, Month 1, Month 2, Month 3, Month 4, Month 5. Y-axis: Sales index where launch month = 100. Two series: 'Cities with competitor entry or heavy discounting (7 cities)' and 'Cities with no major competitor change (11 cities)'. Use illustrative values showing very similar decline patterns. Competitor-change cities: 100, 108, 101, 92, 84, 76. No-competitor-change cities: 100, 106, 99, 91, 85, 78. Add a note or subtitle: 'Both groups decline at nearly the same rate by early fall despite competitor moves occurring in only 7 of 18 cities.' Emphasize that the bars for the two groups are close together each month, with only small differences and both peaking slightly after launch before falling steadily.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Line chart comparing web page request timing by region. X-axis label: 'Request phase'. Y-axis label: 'Time (ms)'. Show two series: 'Affected region' and 'Normal region'. Request phases on the x-axis in this order: 'DNS lookup', 'TCP/TLS connect', 'Request sent', 'Waiting for first byte', 'Content transfer'. Use illustrative values that match the finding: Normal region = 20, 80, 15, 420, 260 ms. Affected region = 25, 85, 18, 430, 3200 ms. The first four phases should appear nearly identical between regions, while 'Content transfer' is dramatically higher for the affected region. Add a note in the chart subtitle: 'Server processing time remains normal; slowdown occurs during data transfer after first byte.'",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Line chart showing network quality over time for the affected region during the incident. X-axis: Time of day from 12:00 to 20:00. Left Y-axis: Packet loss percentage from 0% to 8%. Right Y-axis: Delayed retransmissions per minute from 0 to 160. Series 1: 'Packet loss %' with intermittent bursts: 12:00 0.2%, 13:00 0.4%, 14:00 3.8%, 15:00 5.6%, 16:00 1.1%, 17:00 0.3%, 18:00 4.9%, 19:00 6.7%, 20:00 0.5%. Series 2: 'Delayed retransmissions/min' rising during the same periods: 12:00 8, 13:00 12, 14:00 65, 15:00 110, 16:00 38, 17:00 20, 18:00 95, 19:00 140, 20:00 25. Add a third series as a line or bars for 'Regional page load time (s)' on a secondary overlay scale from 0 to 12 seconds: 12:00 2.1, 13:00 2.4, 14:00 6.8, 15:00 8.9, 16:00 7.2, 17:00 6.5, 18:00 9.1, 19:00 10.4, 20:00 7.0. The visual should highlight that packet loss and retransmission spikes align with some slow periods, but page load time remains abnormally high even during quieter intervals such as 16:00, 17:00, and 20:00, suggesting an additional latency issue beyond pure packet drops.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Line chart comparing page-load time by test region and page size. X-axis: test location grouped by region with cities listed as Seattle, San Francisco, Denver, Dallas, New York, London, Tokyo, and Sydney. Y-axis: total page load time in seconds from 0 to 10. Show three series for page size: Small page (200 KB), Medium page (1.2 MB), and Large page (4.5 MB). Values should show the affected nearby region as consistently slower but not failing: Seattle 1.2 / 2.0 / 3.1, San Francisco 4.0 / 6.2 / 8.4, Denver 3.8 / 5.9 / 8.1, Dallas 1.4 / 2.3 / 3.5, New York 1.3 / 2.1 / 3.2, London 1.5 / 2.4 / 3.6, Tokyo 1.4 / 2.2 / 3.4, Sydney 1.6 / 2.5 / 3.7. Include a note or visual emphasis that the slowdown is concentrated in cities near one region and becomes more pronounced as page size increases, while all tests still complete successfully.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Line chart showing app server health metrics over a 30-minute slowdown window. X-axis: Time from 14:00 to 14:30. Left Y-axis: Percent / counts, labeled 'CPU %, Memory %, Queue Length'. Right Y-axis: Response Time (ms). Include four series with a legend: 'CPU Usage', 'Memory Usage', 'Avg Response Time', and 'Request Queue Length'. Use illustrative values that stay mostly stable: CPU Usage around 34%, 36%, 35%, 33%, 37%, 35% across the window; Memory Usage around 61%, 61%, 62%, 62%, 61%, 61%; Avg Response Time near baseline at 118 ms, 121 ms, 124 ms, 119 ms, 122 ms, 120 ms. Show one brief spike in Request Queue Length centered around 14:12 to 14:16: values 2, 3, 18, 26, 11, 3, then back to 2. Add a subtle annotation at the queue spike: 'Brief queue buildup while unaffected regions still saw normal page loads.' Overall visual should emphasize that server CPU, memory, and response time remain healthy and stable, with only a short-lived queue increase.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "A detailed architectural inspection image of an interior upper-floor stone wall with two tall window openings. Show several prominent new diagonal cracks starting at the upper corners of the windows and running upward toward the ceiling at roughly 35–45 degree angles. These new cracks should look fresh: sharp-edged, light-colored exposed stone or mortar inside the crack line, with clean surfaces and no dark staining, dust buildup, or weathering. On the same wall, include a few much thinner older hairline cracks at similar diagonal angles near other window corners; these older cracks should appear faint, slightly darker, and less distinct, suggesting age and stability. The wall should be old stone masonry with plaster or mortar joints visible, consistent with a century-old building interior. Include the ceiling line at the top of the frame and enough of the wall to compare crack patterns around multiple windows. Emphasize the visual contrast between new and old cracking: new cracks wider and brighter, old cracks narrow and muted.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "A realistic exterior inspection image of a century-old stone building foundation shown in split view or side-by-side comparison. Left side focuses on the east foundation wall: exposed stone blocks with a continuous dark damp band running horizontally along the base, approximately 1 foot high. Several stones within this damp band have visible soft, powdery, eroded surface patches, with light gray-beige crumbling texture and rough flaking areas. The mortar near the base looks worn and slightly recessed. Right side focuses on the west foundation wall: similar stone blocks with a few isolated damp patches lower down near ground level, but the stones remain solid, intact, and firm-looking with no powdery erosion. Ground at both sides is bare soil or sparse grass close to the wall. Lighting should emphasize the contrast between the east side’s widespread moisture damage and the west side’s limited dampness without surface decay. No people, no tools, no labels in the scene.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "A realistic cutaway illustration of the same exterior wall section of a century-old stone building, shown from basement through fourth floor. Emphasize the physical condition difference by floor. The basement and ground floor stones are tightly bonded with intact mortar joints: mortar appears dense, hard, and continuous, with no visible gaps. On the third and fourth floors, the mortar is visibly deteriorated: pale, powdery, crumbly texture, missing chunks in several joints, loose grains falling out, and multiple open gaps between stones about fingertip width. Include a pocket knife at one upper-floor joint scraping away mortar easily, with crumbs collecting below, and a human fingertip near another joint to show the gap size. Keep the same stone type and structural bay alignment across all floors so the contrast is clearly due to mortar condition, not different construction. Add subtle labels: 'Basement', 'Ground Floor', 'Third Floor', 'Fourth Floor', and callouts reading 'Hard, intact mortar' on the lower levels and 'Soft, crumbling mortar with open joints' on the upper levels. The visual should focus on texture, erosion, and material failure rather than architectural style.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "A realistic exterior building-condition image focused on the east side of a century-old stone building. Show a tall stone wall viewed at a slight angle, with a roofline gutter at the top right that appears to be leaking or overflowing. From the gutter area, a wide vertical stain runs down the masonry for several stories: darker damp discoloration near the top fading into lighter brown and gray streaks, with visible white mineral deposits and crusty efflorescence along mortar joints and stone faces. At the base of this wall, show a strip of soil that is visibly darker, muddier, and wetter than surrounding ground, with a damp patch extending outward 1 to 2 meters. Contrast this with adjacent sides of the building visible in the background, where the stone appears dry and evenly colored and the soil looks lighter and dry. Include subtle upper-floor cracks in the east wall masonry to connect to the scenario, but keep the main emphasis on the exterior moisture evidence. Add a simple inset comparison panel showing two handheld moisture meter readings indoors: east wall reading around 18% and north wall reading around 15%, indicating only a slight difference despite the heavy exterior staining. The overall visual should emphasize that the strongest signs of water exposure are outside on the east wall, especially below the gutter and at the saturated soil line.",
  "kind": "image"
}
